;; appendix-l-publishing-share-url.book.slatl

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(appendix
  :book                "Book of Narrative Games"
  :letter              "L"
  :title               "Publishing to a Share URL"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"Your game is done. Playtested. Fixed. Ready. Now you send it to
someone who has never played a Motoi Scheme program in their life.

They should not need to install anything. They should not need to
create an account. They should click a link, and after a second of
loading, they should be in your kitchen scene, pressing A for the
red door.

This appendix is how.

---

## The card

A card is a self-contained runnable. Wrap your game as a card and
you have something publishable.

```scheme
(define-card 'my-narrative-game
  :title \"the beekeeper's daughter\"
  :author \"your name here\"
  :estimated-time \"25-40 minutes\"
  :audience :teen-and-up
  :description
    \"You come home after six months away. Your sister is missing.\n    You have three days.\"
  :init run-beekeepers-daughter)
```

Metadata fields:
- `:title` — what appears in the browser tab and share preview
- `:author` — you
- `:estimated-time` — helps players decide if they have time
- `:audience` — `:child` `:teen-and-up` `:adult`
- `:description` — one or two lines for the share preview
- `:init` — the function that starts the game

The `:init` function is called when the player loads the card. It
should set up the scene and then start playing.

---

## The share URL

Publishing gives you a URL.

```scheme
;; Publish the card. Returns a URL string.
(define my-url (define-card-publish 'my-narrative-game))
```

The URL is something like `https://motoi.example/play/abc123`. It
is public — anyone with the URL can play. It does NOT require an
account for the player.

Copy the URL. Paste it into a message. Send to a friend. They open
it. They are playing your game.

If you want to unpublish, `(define-card-unpublish 'my-narrative-game)`
takes the URL down. Existing links stop working.

---

## The share preview

When someone pastes your URL into a message, most chat apps generate
a preview. That preview uses your card's title, description, and (if
you set one) a preview image.

```scheme
(define-card 'my-narrative-game
  :title \"the beekeeper's daughter\"
  :description \"You come home. Your sister is missing.\"
  :preview-image 'beehive-illustration
  ;; ... other fields ...
  )
```

`:preview-image` is a named asset in the substrate — either a
pre-existing sprite or an image you uploaded.

Preview matters. It is the difference between someone clicking your
link and someone scrolling past it.

---

## Per-player Cortex

When your published game runs, the runtime gives each player their
own isolated Cortex scope. Player A's `state/first-choice` does not
affect Player B's.

This is automatic. You do NOT need to add player-id namespacing
yourself. Just write `(cortex/write 'state/whatever value)` — the
runtime scopes it to the current player.

Sessions persist per player, too. Player A closes the tab and opens
tomorrow — their Cortex is still there.

---

## Anonymous vs signed-in

Players can play anonymously (default). Their Cortex is scoped to
their browser's anonymous session — persistent for the browser, but
lost if they clear cookies or switch devices.

Players who sign in have a stable identity — their Cortex follows
them across devices.

Your card does not need to know which is which. Write to Cortex; the
runtime handles the scoping.

If your game has a 'save your progress across devices' feature you
want to encourage, add a small note:

```scheme
(unless (or (cortex/read 'system/signed-in?)
            (cortex/read 'system/dismissed-signin-nudge?))
  (paint-text 20 500 \"Tip: sign in to keep your progress across devices.\")
  (paint-text 20 525 \"[press S to sign in, or ESC to dismiss]\"))
```

Small nudge, no pressure. Player who dismisses never sees it again.

---

## The load screen

When someone opens your URL, there is a brief moment of loading.
the Motoi runtime handles that automatically — but if your game has
large assets (audio, sprites), the load may take a few seconds.

Add a loading scene:

```scheme
(define (loading-scene)
  (scene/imagine)
  (surface/paper)
  (paint-text 300 300 \"loading...\"))

;; Then, when assets are ready:
(define (init-with-loading)
  (loading-scene)
  (async-load-assets
    (lambda ()
      (run-beekeepers-daughter))))
```

The player sees 'loading…' for two seconds instead of a blank
screen. Small detail, big polish.

---

## Analytics — what you learn about players

If you want to see how many people play your game, and how far they
get, wire lightweight analytics:

```scheme
(define (log-scene-entry scene-name)
  (cortex/write 'analytics/last-scene scene-name)
  (cortex/write 'analytics/scenes-visited
    (cons scene-name
          (or (cortex/read 'analytics/scenes-visited) '()))))
```

You (the author) can then query aggregate stats: how many players
reached ch3, how many finished, how many quit at ch5.

DO respect player privacy. Do NOT log the content of things they
type. Do NOT log identifying details. Log only scene ids and
timestamps.

---

## Multi-player narrative (advanced)

For games where two friends play the same story with different
Cortex — say, a two-player mystery where each has separate clues —
use per-player Cortex scoping.

```scheme
(define (player-write key value)
  (let ((pid (or (cortex/read 'system/current-player-id) 'p1)))
    (cortex/write
      (string->symbol
        (string-append \"player/\" (symbol->string pid) \"/\"
                       (symbol->string key)))
      value)))

(define (player-read key)
  (let ((pid (or (cortex/read 'system/current-player-id) 'p1)))
    (cortex/read
      (string->symbol
        (string-append \"player/\" (symbol->string pid) \"/\"
                       (symbol->string key))))))
```

Switch `system/current-player-id` when it's the other player's turn.
Reads and writes go into the right namespace.

For a full two-player system with real-time sync, you need more
infrastructure than this appendix covers. This pattern is for
turn-based couch-coop.

---

## Sharing beyond one friend

If your game gets popular, several things can happen:

**Word of mouth.** Players share the URL themselves. Nothing you
need to do.

**Curated collections.** the runtime's platform may feature your game in
a 'kids' games' or 'first-timer' collection. This is by editorial
review.

**Direct search.** Players search for narrative games by keyword;
your card's title and description determine whether you show up.

Write good metadata. It matters more than you think.

---

## Updates

Your game will get better. You will fix bugs, add scenes, rework
endings. When you republish, existing URLs continue to work — they
point at the newest version.

Player saves may or may not survive the update (see appendix H on
migration). Test carefully.

If your update is BIG — new act, major structural changes — consider
publishing as a new card. Old URL stays with the old version;
players discover the new version separately.

---

## Removing your game

If you want to take your game down, unpublish.

```scheme
(define-card-unpublish 'my-narrative-game)
```

Existing URLs immediately return 'this game is no longer available.'
Cortex data is preserved for a grace period (in case you republish);
after that, it may be deleted.

You can always republish later. `define-card-publish` again — same
card id — gives you a new URL that reads the old Cortex data.

---

## The one-shot cart

For a really small game — a two-minute playable poem, a five-minute
short — you might skip the card wrapper entirely and just share a
raw Scheme file. Anyone with a Motoi Scheme runtime can load and
run it.

This is fine for kids sharing with friends who are already coders.
For sharing with people who are NOT coders, use the card.

---

## The moment

Someone opens your URL. Your kitchen appears. They press A. They
walk through the red door. They are playing YOUR game.

This is the moment the book has been building toward. Everything —
Cortex, story trees, dialogue, body language, camera, sound,
consequences, companion, save slots — was for this.

Send the URL to someone you love. Wait to hear back. Take notes on
their reaction. Then write the next one.

---

## Summary

Wrap in a card. Publish for a URL. Player runs it in a browser
with no install. Cortex scopes per-player. Add a loading scene for
polish. Log analytics respectfully. Multi-player is possible with
extra scoping. Updates preserve URLs. Unpublish takes it down.

Send the link. Wait. Iterate. That is the shape of publishing
narrative games.")
